Solution:

Enum is a special keyword in C++ programming that allows programmer to define sets of values with the help of a name which is used instead of integer literals. There are different types of enumerations in C++, and they include:

1. Char Identifiers: These are defined using the "typedef enum" keyword. Example:
```c++
typedef enum{RED, GREEN, BLUE} Color;
```
2. One-Value Enumeration: These are defined using the "enum" keyword, and they can hold a single value. Example:
```c++
enum {False, True}
```
3. Multi-Value Enumerations: These are defined using the "enum" keyword and can hold multiple values. Example:
```c++
enum {RED = 1, GREEN = 2}
```
4. Two-Value Enumerations: These are defined using the "enum" keyword and can hold only two values. Example:
```c++
enum {RED = 1, GREEN = 2, BLUE = 3}
```
Examples of using enumerations in code:

Example 1:
```c++
enum Color {RED, GREEN, BLUE};

/// Prints color value to the console.
void printColor(Color c) {
    switch (c) {
        case RED:
            printf("Red\n");
            break;
        case GREEN:
            printf("Green\n");
            break;
        case BLUE:
            printf("Blue\n");
            break;
        default:
            printf("Unknown color\n");
            break;
    }
}
